<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN370-intro">
      <p type="edition">tiṇaiyum tuṟaiyum avai. cōḻaṉ ceruppāḻiyeṟinta iḷañcēṭceṉṉiyai ūṉpoti pacuṅkuṭaiyār.
      </p>
      <p xml:lang="en" type="translation">  
      </p>
    </div> 
    <div xml:id="PN370">
      <lg type="edition">
<l><gap quantity="38" reason="lost" unit="character"/> ḷi,</l>
<l>nārum pōḻuñ ceytuṇ ṭōrāṅkup</l>
<l>pacitiṉat tiraṅkiya virumpē rokkaṟ</l>
<l>kārpataṅ kaṇṇeṉa mātiran tuḻaii</l>
<l>vēruḻan tulaṟi maruṅku<supplied>cet to</supplied>ḻiyavan</l>
<l>tattak kuṭiñait tuṭimaru ṭīṅkura</l>
<l>luḻuñcilaṅ kavaṭṭiṭai yirunta paruntiṉ</l>
<l>peṭaipayir kuralō ṭicaikku māṅkaṭ</l>
<l>kaḻaikāyn tulaṟi<supplied>ya vaṟaṅkūr nīḷiṭai</supplied></l>
<l>varimaraṟ ṟiraṅkiya kāṉam piṟpaṭap</l>
<l>paḻumara muḷḷiya paṟavai pōla</l>
<l>voṇpaṭai māri vīḻkaṉi peyteṉat</l>
<l>tuvaitteḻu kuruti nilamicaip parappa</l>
<l>viḷainta <supplied>ceḻuṅ</supplied>kura larintukāl kuvittup</l>
<l><supplied>paṭupiṇam</supplied> palpōr paḻiya vāṅki</l>
<l>yerutukaḷi ṟāka vāṇmaṭa lōcci</l>
<l>yatari tiritta vāḷuku kaṭāvi</l>
<l>ṉakaṉkaṭ ṭaṭāri teḷirppa voṟṟi</l>
<l>ventiṟal viyaṉkaḷam polikeṉ ṟētti</l>
<l>yiruppumukañ ceṟitta vēnteḻiṉ maruppiṉ</l>
<l>varaimaruṇ mukavaikku vantaṉeṉ peruma</l>
<l>vaṭinavi leḵkam pāynteṉak kiṭanta</l>
<l>toṭiyuṭait taṭakkai yōcci veruvā</l>
<l>riṉattaṭi virāya varikkuṭa raṭaicci</l>
<l>yaḻukuraṟ pēymaka ḷayarak kaḻukoṭu</l>
<l>ceñcevi yeruvai tiritaru</l>
<l>mañcuvaru kiṭakkaiya kaḷaṅkiḻa vōyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Coming to stay behind in exhaustion on the side, the roots having endured [and] whithered, (5)</l>
<l>stirring the great directions like eyes, a full right consistency (4)</l>
<l>for the very big kinfolk that is dried up when gnawed by hunger (3)</l>
<l>like one with preparing, [and] eating fibres and leather straps (2)</l>
<l>like a bat that remembered the ripening tree, (11)</l>
<l>while the forest is left behind, where bowstring hemp in rows has dried (10)</l>
<l>on the long way abounding in drought, where the bamboo has become hot [and] withered, (9)</l>
<l>in that place where, with the calling voice of the female</l>
<l>of the kite that was perched among the dry branches of the Sirissa,</l>
<l>the sweet voice resembling the Tuṭi drum of the owl on the road sounds, (6-8)</l>
<l>praising “may the wide field of hot vigour flourish, (19)</l>
<l>pressing, so that they sound, the wide-eyed Taṭāri drum (18)</l>
<l>of buffalo[-hide?] shed by the men that made the thrashing oxen turn (17)</l>
<l>raising sword blades, elephants as oxen, (16)</l>
<l>dragging, for them to be destroyed(?), many heaps of falling corpses, (15)</l>
<l>heaping legs, cutting ripened rich ears, (14)</l>
<l>while the rising blood spreads in the ground, making noise, (13)</l>
<l>as descending ripe fruit rain down in the rain of bright weapons,” (12)</l>
<l>I have come, o great man, for the mountain-like gifts you have drawn (20)</l>
<l>with eminent graceful tusks whose faces are fitted with iron. (19)</l>
<l>lord of the battle field with frightful expanses, (27)</l>
<l>where red-eared kites move (26)</l>
<l>along with vultures, while female Pēy with weepy voice engage (25)</l>
<l>in inserting bowels in lines mixed with the flesh of groups (24)</l>
<l>that were not frightened, wielding in [their] bangled broad hand (23)</l>
<l>the sharp blades that lie [around] because they had leapt. (22)</l>
</lg>
